 every one of the boxes for Everquest, Ruins of Kunark, and Scars of Velious, it is clearly stated that Windows 95 is supported.  For example, here is exactly what is listed on the side of my Scars of Velious box:<br>
<br>
Operating System: Windows 95/98/00<br>
Processor: Pentium 200<br>
RAM: 64MB<br>
Video Card: Direct3D or Glide compliant accelerator card with 16MB video ram<br>
Sound Card: DirectX 7.0a compatible sound card<br>
Modem: 28.8k + internet connection<br>
*CR-ROM: 2X speed CD-ROM<br>
Hard Drive Space: 600 MB +<br>
<br>
*CR-ROM is a typo on the box, but hey, I wanted to list exactly what it said so you can't be confused.<br>
<br>
Now, I know that recently Verant posted on the official message board that they would be upgrading to DirectX 8.1.  Well, actually, the post is rather unclear since the post seems to use DirectX 8.1 and DirectX 8 interchangeably.  The problem here is that 8 is supported by Win95, but 8.1 is not.  Nowhere in that entire thread does it ever state that EQ would no longer support Win95.<br>
<br>
I claim that this is very close to false advertising which is illegal.  We purchased the game and our machines met or exceeded the system requirements to play.  Now, in order for my roommate to play EQ, he has to purchase a copy of Windows 98.  This is wrong.  If Microsoft suddenly said, &quot;Sorry guys, but we just came out with Word 2002 and now all of you people running Word 3.0 have to upgrade to Windows XP in order for Word 3.0 to run properly&quot;, there would be lawsuits all over the place.  <br>
<br>
I know that Shadows of Luclin requires Win 98, and that is fine.  My problem is that the previous game and expansions now require it.  So you are pretty much out of luck if you did not want to purchase Shadows of Luclin.  Upgrading the version of DirectX that the original Everquest uses is also fine, as long as those versions of DirectX are supported by the operating systems listed as the system requirements since the DirectX updates are free downloads from Microsoft.  Forcing people to pay for an upgrade in order to use a piece of software that they have been using for 2+ years with basically no problems is very very wrong.<br>
<br>
Note:  If you look at the Microsoft site which talks about DirectX 8.1, you get this bit of text:<br>
<br>
Q. Why won't DirectX 8.1 install on Windows 95?<br>
<br>
A. With very few exceptions game titles that require DirectX 8.1 will also require a computer new enough that it was built with Windows 98 or a more recent version installed. This is because modern games require processor speeds in excess of the fastest processors used by Windows 95. Current and future games that will run under Windows 95 should always work with DirectX 8.0a or earlier.<br>
<br>
This clearly states that if a game was to run under Windows 95, it should only use DirectX 8.oa or earlier.<br>
<br>
One other note:  You CANNOT CANCEL YOUR ACCOUNT IF YOU ARE RUNNING WIN95.  He cannot run Everquest in order to cancel his account.  That, my friends, is VERY illegal. <p>Sbik Swashbucklugget<br>
